\f0\b\fs44 \cf2 \up0 \nosupersub \ulnone Your House Is Wasting Energy Right Now
\f1\b0\fs26 \cf3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\i \cf4 How a smart energy management system pays for itself \'97 and how you and AI can build one fitted exactly to your home
\f1\i0 \cf3 \
\
Here's a question worth sitting with: what percentage of the energy your home consumes right now is actually being used by anyone? Maybe first we should explain why that matters to you. Energy used to be cheap and fairly reliable. It\'92s not now, and it\'92s going to get a lot more expensive\'97soon. The time to do something about that is NOT when you can\'92t afford to keep your home comfortable. It\'92s now. \
\
If you're at work, the answer  to how much power is actually being used by anyone is probably close to zero. But your water heater is keeping 50 gallons at 120\'b0F. Your thermostat is maintaining a comfortable temperature in rooms nobody is sitting in. And depending on what your home is like some other loads are running for the benefit of no one, burning energy so the house will be ready when you walk back through the door.\
\
That sounds kind of stupid when you think about it, but it wasn\'92t worth fixing when energy was cheap. Now it\'92s expensive, and I\'92ve built a cheap way to fix it\'97that will deliver a return on investment almost immediately.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf3 \
\pard\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs34 \cf2 How Do We Fix This?\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs26 \cf3 This description isn\'92t the entire system. It\'92s just one part of a more complex whole. But this part is easy to describe and understand. The system you build will do a lot more, and we\'92ll get to that. We\'92re going to describe this as if there were just one person living at your home. but of course it can be everyone who actually lives there. Here we go:\
\
Your phone knows where you are. It also knows your speed, your direction, and your likely destination. Every navigation app on the planet uses this data. Your energy management system can too.\
\
The basic concept: when your phone crosses an outbound radius around your home, the system knows you've left. It adjusts your home to suit no one being there. Water heater drops to a maintenance temperature. Thermostat backs off \'97 not to off, just enough to stop fighting physics. If it's 90\'b0F outside and nobody's home, there's no reason to keep the house at 72\'b0F. Let it drift to 82\'b0F. At that differential, heat transfer from outside nearly stops, and it takes almost no energy to hold it there.\
\
When you head home, your phone crosses the inbound radius.
\fs24 Your phone's location data includes velocity and heading. Once the system sees you moving toward home at highway speed, it can calculate your arrival time within a few minutes and stage the recovery accordingly. Walk in the door and everything is normal. Not cold. Not stuffy. Not twenty minutes behind. You\'92ll never notice the difference\'97 except on your utility bill.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0
\cf3 In the addendum we talk about price\'97that\'92s for the hardware, which is off the shelf stuff. The software, which is really the system, is free. Built on open source software, using AI at the free or cheap level to implement, customize and configure. No subscriptions, no cloud, smart, very capable, expandable, and free. 
\fs26 \
\pard\sa160\partightenfactor0

