\f0\b\fs34 \cf2 What It Looks Like Day to Day\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs26 \cf3 Morning departure: Both phones leave the property. Water heater drops to holding temperature. Pool filtration shifts to a midday solar window. Phantom loads cut power to standby devices. HVAC drops load to a minimum level that protects your home (appliances, pipes, etc). You decide what that is. \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4\b \cf3 Midday solar peak:
\f1\b0  Production exceeds consumption. Excess power routes to the water heater \'97 heating for free. Battery tops up. Pool pump runs its full cycle.\
\

\f4\b Homeward bound: 
\f1\b0 Phones detected moving toward home at highway speed. Arrival time calculated. Climate adjusted to reach comfort settings on schedule. You walk in to a normal house.\
\

\f4\b Utility peak hours:
\f1\b0  Battery discharges to cover household loads. Grid draw drops to near zero during the most expensive rate window. Battery recharges from solar the next morning.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f4\b \cf3 Away for a week:
\f1\b0  System drops to minimal maintenance mode \'97 water heater at minimum safe temperature, pool on minimum filtration, everything else off. Estimated savings versus normal operation: 40\'9660% of weekly energy cost.\
\pard\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs34 \cf2 The Honest Caveats\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs26 \cf3 Location-based automation works well when phones are reliable \'97 but phones lose coverage, run out of battery, and occasionally get left behind. Graceful fallback logic for those edge cases is still being refined. We\'92ve made it a little better by using the HA companion app installed on our phones instead of just native phone capabilities, but I\'92d like it to be a bit more reliable. \
\
The setup requires some technical comfort. The AI-configured model lowers the bar considerably, but you still need to be comfortable with basic command-line operations. That's a real constraint, but it\'92s relatively easy to overcome.\
\
And like any automation system, it needs tuning. The first few weeks involve calibration \'97 adjusting location radii, getting recovery timing right, learning actual patterns. It gets better with use.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0
\cf3 We\'92re still building this. If someone wanted a version today I could jump ahead, cobble together something useful, and give them a file from my git repo to dump into their instance of Claude.ai. None of these are showstoppers. They're just honest.\
\pard\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs34 \cf2 Where This Is Going\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs26 \cf3 My Maui house is an unusual test environment \'97 no heat or AC, mild climate, off-grid guest house. The real test will be our house in Hood River, Oregon: proper winters, real HVAC, time-of-use utility rates, and a lifestyle involving a lot of coming and going. I'll be documenting that build-out as it happens.\
\
The knowledge file \'97 the AI deployment package that makes all of this buildable by anyone \'97 is in active development. The goal is a document any homeowner can load into their Claude Project and use to build a system precisely fitted to their home, in an afternoon.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0
\cf3 If you're interested in building something like this, or already running Home Assistant and want to compare notes, I'd like to hear from you. The whole point of doing this in the open is that it gets better when more people are working on it.\
\pard\sa400\partightenfactor0

